Reevaluated 
<H4>    Justice Minister, Police Official on `Reprioritizing' </H4>
Resources 

<F P=102> 94WD0269G Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE in Danish 1 Mar 94 p 
1 </F>

<F P=103> 94WD0269G </F>
<F P=104>  Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE </F>
<F P=105>  Danish </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Lotte Mejlhede and Mikkel Thrane: ``Narcotics </F>
Police To Be Reinforced''] 
  [Text] ``You can take a dart and throw it at a map of the 
country. Wherever it happens to land, you could open a drug 
case.'' 
  Per Kanding, chief of the national police force's mobile 
squad, believes that too little is being done to counter the 
growing drug problem. 
  ``Many small police districts are not doing enough in drug 
cases. They do not have the resources. After all, the drug trade 
is not a crime that is reported and, as a result, drug cases are 
often put on the back burner in favor of crimes that are 
reported,'' Kanding said. 
  He believes there must be a reprioritizing of police 
resources if we are really interested in doing something in this 
area. He is supported in this by Justice Minister Erling Olsen 
(Social Democrat). 
  ``The police will not get more resources, but those we have 
must be used differently. I would like to see the effort against 
organized crime--including drug crimes--be strengthened. 
Consequently, some policemen must accept being shifted to other 
duties.'' He did not wish to reveal what jobs the police would 
no longer do, but he was certain enough police could be 
transferred. 
  Yesterday the United Nations published its annual report for 
1993. It revealed that the global drug trade was becoming more 
extensive and more aggressive. In particular, Denmark must 
protect itself from drugs being brought in by way of the chaotic 
countries of East Europe. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

