<H3> <TI>   Presidential Candidates, Sintura, Pardo React to Taboada </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Presidential Candidates, Sintura, Pardo React to Taboada </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Remarks 

<F P=102>   PA2304030194 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Canal 
A in Spanish 0000 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2304030194 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Canal 
A </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report from the "Seven O'Clock Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] Reaction from the country's political circles to the 
outrageous hearing held by the U.S. Senate Subcommittee on 
Terrorism, Narcotics, and International Operations were not long 
in coming. Several presidential candidates, who according to 
Gabriel Taboada are in the pay of drug traffickers, had this to 
say today. [begin recording] 
  Andres Pastrana, Conservative Party presidential 
candidate: I am concerned to see that the attempt to 
besmirch Colombia's name continues. When a person makes 
accusations, he should name names. That is what the country 
needs. If he has names, let him say so. It is important that 
the country know if there is drug money in the political 
campaigns. The information must come out. As far as I am 
concerned, I am absolutely certain there is no drug money. I 
have just given my records to the Overseer of the National 
Treasury, to the National Electoral Council, and to the 
Colombian people. People cannot continue making these 
accusations. 
  Antonio Navarro Wolff, presidential candidate for 19 
April Movement Democratic Alliance: I say categorically 
that Antonio Navarro and Jesus Pinacue have not received a penny 
from drug traffickers for their campaign. I am not familiar 
with the rest of Mr. Taboada's statement, and it is hard to 
comment on something with which I am unfamiliar. 
  Enrique Parejo, presidential candidate of the National 
Democratic Alternative: Some of what was said reflects what 
many Colombians have been saying. There is drug money in the 
political campaigns, and there has been in the past. Drug money 
has infiltrated institutions. That is a fact, and I have 
denounced it. [end recording] 
  The government and the Prosecutor General's Office commented 
on the matter. [begin recording] 
  Deputy Prosecutor General Francisco Sintura: 
Senator Kerry, respect Colombian justice and do not get too 
close to rogues. 
  Defense Minister Rafael Pardo: Those remarks 
cannot be taken seriously. They reflect an ill-intended 
distortion to harm a country that has suffered a great deal from 
drug trafficking. It is not justified to give credence to 
someone who has no information and no way to get any and whose 
charges are not serious. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

