<H3> <TI>   Mulino Says No U.S. Reply to Protest Note Received </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mulino Says No U.S. Reply to Protest Note Received </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2004020494 Panama City Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 
2300 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2004020494 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City Circuito RPC Television </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Mara Rivera; from the "RPC Television News" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] The Foreign Ministry is waiting for the U.S. reply 
to the protest note it has sent in connection with the charges 
money is being laundered in Panama. 
  Foreign Minister Jose Raul Mulino has said a protest note 
was 
sent due to the U.S. charges the Panamanian Government has links 
with drug traffickers. He has said although the note was sent 
last week, there has still been no reply, but he excused the 
United States by saying it is possible the letter is being 
studied. 
  [Begin Mulino recording] As I have said many times, I have 
not said no crimes are committed. An economy such as ours, due 
to the openness with which the service and banking sectors are 
handled, could well be used for criminal acts. What I cannot 
accept is to say the authorities are behind this. 
  In the cases where crimes have been detected, we have taken 
action according to the law. If there are other cases about 
which someone knows or if some government has information a 
certain bank might be involved, it is their duty to report this 
at the highest level--like, check this out; this is what is 
happening; correct it. Briefly, this is what the note I have 
sent the United States says. [end recording] 
  Mulino expressed his desire to hold a meeting in Panama, 
which he requested in the note, to speak broadly about the topic 
and at the highest level. 

</TEXT>

