<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> GEORGIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   National Bureau To Combat Drug Addiction Created </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    National Bureau To Combat Drug Addiction Created </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2204181094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1623 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2204181094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In accordance with the decree signed by Georgian 
leader Eduard Shevardnadze on Friday, a national bureau to fight 
drug addiction and drug business has been created in Georgia. 
The bureau has been created on the basis of the department in 
charge for fighting drug addiction within Georgia's Interior 
Ministry in order to strengthen the fight against drug addiction 
and the drug business. 
  A section in charge for supervision over the cases on 
illegal 
circulation of narcotics and psychotropic substances is being 
created in the republic's prosecutor's office "to observe 
legislation with respect to fighting drugs." 
  The republic's customs department has been commissioned to 
create services to prevent transit of drugs through the border. 
  The decree stresses that the difficult social-economic 
situation in Georgia, aggravation of the criminal situation, 
weakening of border control have facilitated the spread of drug 
addiction in Georgia. Spreading of drug addiction among young 
people arouses special concern. In addition, the drug mafia is 
showing an interest in Georgia as a country which is convenient 
for drug transit. 
  Vice Premier Irakly Menagarishvili, chairman of the 
governmental commission on drug fighting declared at a 
conference on Friday in Tbilisi that there are about 100,000 
drug addicts in Georgia now, more than 200,000 have died as a 
result of their addiction. He said that these are predominantly 
young people aged 16-20. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

