BFN 

  [Excerpt] The Russian-Hungarian treaty on burying processed 
nuclear fuel on the territory of our country is quite 
advantageous for Russia, Viktor Mikhaylov, minister of nuclear 
power engineering, told INTERFAX. Let me remind you that during 
his visit to Hungary Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin signed 
an agreement under which processed nuclear fuel from Hungarian 
nuclear power stations is to be brought to Russia, for which our 
country is to be paid $40 million. Here is a report from our 
correspondent. 
  Correspondent Yevgeniya Novikova: Russia is still 
receiving radioactive waste from foreign nuclear power stations 
under international agreements once concluded by the Soviet 
Union. This concerns only those stations that were built by the 
Soviet Union on its neighbors' territory, and with which 
appropriate agreements were concluded. According to Greenpeace, 
processed nuclear fuel is currently stored on the territory of 
combines in Chelyabinsk and Krasnoyarsk, where the ecological 
situation has already caused a high incidence of radiation 
sickness and oncological diseases among the population. [passage 
omitted] 

