<F P=100> EAST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Danube Environment Committee Reports Progress </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Danube Environment Committee Reports Progress </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1603190094 Sofia BTA in English 1506 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1603190094 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Silistra, March 16 (BTA) -- The tenth session of the 
Mixed Bulgarian Romanian Commission on Environmental Problems in 
the Silistra-Calarasi Region, held in Calarasi, decided to 
propose to the environment ministries of the two countries, to 
introduce Western European standards in environment monitoring 
in Bulgaria and Romania, Dr. Marin Peychev, director of the 
Hygiene and Epidemiology Institute in Silistra, told BTA. 
  In the almost ten-month break in the work of the commission, 
the Romanians managed to replace over 80 percent of the 
purification installations of the metallurgical combined works 
in Calarasi which reduced phenol, hydrogen sulphide and dust 
emissions. The Bulgarian Institute of Hygiene, Medical 
Environment and Nutrition carried out joint research with a 
similar Romanian institute. The Romanian side showed interest 
in environment related diseases incidence. The Bulgarian side 
presented the required information and research methods. The 
measurements taken in January and February in Bulgaria have 
shown lower concentrations of pollutants against the same period 
last year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

